{{Infobox language |name=Col |altname= Base Lembak |nativename=Sindang |states=Indonesia |region=[[Sumatra]] |speakers={{sigfig|145,000|2}} |date=2000 census |ref=e18 |familycolor=Austronesian |fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] (MP) |fam3=[[Nuclear Malayo-Polynesian languages|Nuclear MP]] |fam4=[[Malayic languages|Malayic]] |fam5=[[Malayan languages|Malayan]] |fam6= |iso3=liw |glotto=coll1240 |glottorefname=Col }}
'''Col''' (Chol), or '''Lembak''', is a [[Malayan language]] of [[Sumatra]]. It is spoken by around 145,000 speakers (2000) with most speakers can be found in [[Lubuklinggau|Lubuklinggau city]], [[Bengkulu]] and the areas surround it all the way to [[Musi rawas]] in [[South Sumatra]]. The speakers of this language belongs to ethnic Lembak, a small ethnic group closely related to ethnic Malays, especially those of Bengkulu and Palembang Malays. Col is closely related to [[Musi language|Palembang Malay]] and [[Bengkulu language|Bengkulu Malay]] with minor differences mostly in pronunciation, the Bengkulu Malay and Palembang Malay tend to end with "o" while Col usually ends with "e". Col language has its own ISO code that is "liw".
