'''Message discipline''' is the concept that [[politician]]s and other public policy advocates should talk about what is relevant to achieve their aims, and not allow themselves to be sidetracked either by their own thoughts or the questions of [[Mass media|press]] or audience. <!-- Essentially, they should try to manipulate any discussion to mislead voters through "glittering generalities".--> The term is finding its way into business, both in advertising and internal communications.
When a politician repeats the same thing ''ad nauseam'', or uses a question on one subject as a launching point to talk about a different subject, he or she is said to be exercising message discipline. Message discipline may involve a subordination of irrelevant personal opinions, or a subordination of fluctuating desires to say what others want to hear versus maintaining an unwavering devotion to the message as it reaches out to greater numbers of potential audience members.<ref>{{cite book|title=Managing the President's Message: The White House Communications Operation|author=Martha Joynt Kumar|publisher=JHU Press|year=2007|isbn=080188652X}}</ref>
Message discipline is often practiced around [[wedge issue]]s. Devolving to talking points (practicing message discipline) around issues such as same-sex marriage or abortion rights can be a powerful weapon in the politician's arsenal, either clouding a difficult line of questioning from an interviewer, or motivating the candidates' base to vote. Key to defining wedge issues and practicing message discipline are the selection of terms that [[Low information voter|low-information voters]]<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brockington,|first=David|title=A Low Information Theory of Ballot Position Effect|journal=Political Behavior|date=2003-03-01|doi=10.1023/A:1022946710610|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1023/A:1022946710610}}</ref> will rally around.
In a business context, message discipline is the practice of reducing and managing the number of messages<ref>{{cite web|last=McMahon|first=Gavin|title=6 Steps to Message Discipline|url=http://makeapowerfulpoint.com/2011/10/22/message-discipline/|work=Make a Powerful Point|accessdate=21 November 2011}}</ref> going from headquarters and marketing functions to field organizations as well as front-line employees. This goal-oriented, structured, strategic communication, is believed{{by whom?|date=January 2014}} to drive operational excellence in organizations, as it reduces the clutter and mixed messages that sometimes afflict communications through organizational layers.
Message discipline is criticised by educated voters who see it as a method of obfuscation from what the electorate sees as important. Overly simplistic and repeated communications of the message is seen as dumbing downnand can meet with cynicism of the electorate.
