{{Infobox person | name = Sasidharan Arattuvazhy | image =Sasidharan_Aarattuvazhi.jpg | birth_date = {{birth date|1955|08|25}} | death_date = {{death date and age|2001|01|21|1955|08|25}} | nationality = Indian | occupation = Playwright }}
'''Sasidharan Arattuvazhi''' was a [[Malayalam]] [[playwright]] and [[screenwriter]]. Within a career spanning more than two decades, he wrote 20 screenplays and 12 plays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenindia.com/old/20010209/rehap.htm|author=|title=Sasidharan Aarattuvazhi: The interview that never happened|work=|publisher=''[[Screen India]]''|date=February 9, 2002 |accessdate=April 12, 2011}}</ref>
==Biography== Sasi was born at Arattuvazhi in [[Alappuzha district]] as the son of Arjunan Pillai. He liked writing plays while still only in school. His first professional stage play was ''Kolayaali'' (''The Murderer''). Later, when Sasi was studying at S. D. College, [[Alappuzha]], the craze for writing plays besieged him again. He wrote plays and sent them to the [[All India Radio]]. Sasi shifted home base to [[Thiruvananthapuram]], where he worked first as a journalist with magazines such as ''Kudumbakatha'' and ''Kuttikatha''. He then set up his own advertising agency, Primary Colours. He wrote some of his notable stage plays during this time. Inspired by various screenplays of [[M. T. Vasudevan Nair]], he developed a keen interest in writing screenplays for films. He made his flm debut with Kaladharan’s ''[[Nettipattam]]'' (1990). But the film failed both critically and commercially. He was then approached by [[Rajasenan]], for whom he wrote the family drama ''[[Ayalathe Adheham]]''. The film became a resounding hit. With this film, Sasi gained a place with the top-grade screenwriters of Malayalam. He went on to write screenplays for 18 more films, including the cult classic ''[[Yodha (1992 film)|Yoddha]]'', comic thriller ''[[CID Unnikrishnan B.A., B.Ed.]]'', family drama ''[[Kaliveedu]]'', and the hilarious ''Cheppadividya''. ''Yoddha'', which released on 4 September 1992 is widely regarded as his master piece. The film became a landmark film in the history of [[Malayalam cinema]], with its story, scenes, characters and music gaining cult status.
Sasidharan Arattuvazhi died on 21 January 2001. He was 45.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2001/jan/23sasi.htm|author=|title=Sasidharan Arattuvazhi passes away|work=|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|date=January 23, 2001|accessdate=April 12, 2011}}</ref> He was suffering from [[cirrhosis]], attributed by his heavy alcoholism. He is survived by his wife Sudhakutty and two daughters.
==Filmography== * ''[[Aalibabayum Aarara Kallanmarum]]'' (1998) * ''[[Kilukil Pambaram]]'' (1997) * ''[[Avittam Thirunaal Aarogya Sriman]]'' (1995) * ''[[Ayalathe Adheham]]'' (1992) * ''[[Cheppadividya]]'' * ''[[CID Unnikrishnan B.A., B.Ed.]]'' * ''[[Kaliveedu]]'' * ''[[Kudumbakodathi]]'' * ''[[Pidakkozhi Koovunna Noottandu]]'' (1994) * ''[[Porutham]]'' * ''[[Pravachakan]]'' (1993) * ''[[Vardhakyapuranam]]'' * ''[[Yoddha (1992 film)|Yoddha]]'' (1992) *''[[Nettippattam]]'' (1990)
